Here are the symbolizations for each proposition:

[[] AxM(x) & AF(x) []];
[[] Ex(G(x)) []];
[[] Ax∼H(x) []];
[[] Ex(F(x)) & Ay(G(y)⇒ ¬H(x, y)) []]

Explanation:

(1) "All humans have black hair" can be symbolized as "for all x, if x is a human, then x has black hair", which is AxM(x) & AF(x).

(2) "Some people have been to the moon" can be symbolized as "there exists some x such that x has been to the moon", which is Ex(G(x)).

(3) "No one has been to Jupiter" can be symbolized as "for all x, x has not been to Jupiter", which is Ax∼H(x).

(4) "Students studying in the United States are not necessarily Asian" can be symbolized as "there exists some x studying in the United States, and for all y, if y is Asian, then x is not the same as y" (i.e., no student studying in the United States is necessarily Asian). This is Ex(F(x) & Ay(G(y)⇒ ¬H(x, y))).

